# Why the VIGIL workflow // shortcomings of SSH assumptions for remote tele-ops

  SSH requires the robot to accept connections from the internet. 
  We can't control every customer's firewall, so the robot calls us instead,
  and we broker everything through a single, authenticated channel that we control.

## SSH: the inbound port problem
 
  SSH assumes you can reach the device. For a robot on a customer's factory floor or a consumer's home network, that means:
  - The customer has to open a hole in their firewall to port 22
  - Most enterprise IT departments refuse this on principle
  - Robots on cellular (4G/5G) sit behind carrier-grade NAT — they don't have a routable IP at all, full stop
  - Even if the customer agrees, their IP changes, their router reboots, their network guy leaves
  
  You can't build a global fleet operations tool on "please ask each customer to configure their firewall for us."

## SSH: credential chaos at scale

  One robot: manageable. A hundred robots: you have a hundred SSH keys to provision, store, rotate, and revoke. When a support
  engineer leaves the company, you're manually cycling keys on every device they ever touched. There's no central "this person is
   no longer authorized" — you have to find every robot they had access to and remove them individually.
  
  SSH: no access control, no audit

  SSH is binary — you're either in with full shell access, or you're not. There's no "this engineer can restart the navigation
  service but can't touch the data directory." There's no built-in record of which commands ran. Shell history can be disabled,
  logs can be deleted. If a customer asks "what did your engineer do on our robot last Tuesday," the honest answer is "we don't
  know for certain."

