##  VPN: flat network problem
  
  A VPN puts every connected device on the same network segment. That means a compromised robot, a compromised laptop, or a rogue
   employee can probe every other device on the network. You've traded "hard to get in" for "once you're in, everything is
  exposed."

  VPN: customers don't want your network on theirs

  Getting a VPN to work requires either running your VPN server inside the customer's network (most enterprise security teams
  won't allow a vendor to join their internal network) or routing the customer's traffic through your infrastructure (they won't
  trust that either). This is a procurement and legal blocker before it's even a technical one.
  
  VPN: still has the NAT problem

  Traditional VPNs still require an inbound connection to establish the tunnel. Same cellular/NAT problem as SSH. Solutions exist
   (WireGuard, Tailscale) but they're complex to operate at scale across thousands of customer environments you don't control.

  ---
##  Why agent-calls-home solves all of this
  
  The robot only makes outbound TCP connections — to your control plane at a fixed address. Outbound TCP on port 443 is allowed
  on almost every network on earth, including cellular, because it looks like HTTPS traffic. The robot doesn't need an inbound
  port. The customer doesn't need to configure anything.

  Everything else follows from that:
  - Credentials are managed centrally on the control plane — revoke a device or an operator in one place, it takes effect
  everywhere instantly
  - The broker enforces permissions before anything reaches the robot — the robot doesn't need to know who the operator is or
  what they're allowed to do
  - Every command goes through the broker, so every command can be logged, and the log is on infrastructure you control, not on a
   device someone could tamper with
   
  The pattern isn't new — it's how AWS Systems Manager replaces SSH for cloud servers, how modern IoT platforms work, how
  Cloudflare Tunnel works. VIGIL is that pattern for deployed robots, built in Rust, with a tamper-evident audit trail.

